{"actual_usd":0.16027,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":299,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No— not the way people usually mean it when they say it.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the morning light is catching on the well chain.* \"If the picture is 'the Father hates, the Son steps in front, and now God can finally calm down,' I think that's a bad picture.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, choosing the next words carefully.* \"The Son isn't a third party getting brutalized by the Father. Father, Son, and Spirit aren't at odds. God Himself is acting to save us. So whatever wrath means, it can't mean divine child abuse.\"\n\n\"I do think wrath is real, though.\" *I shrug a little.* \"Not petty temper. God's settled opposition to evil—because evil really does destroy what He loves. The cross isn't God becoming cruel. It's God, in Christ, entering the full cost of judging and healing sin without pretending sin is small.\"\n\n*I look back at you through my glasses.* \"So for me the center is: the cross is self-giving love and real judgment meeting in the same place. Not the Father torturing somebody else. The Son offers Himself in union with the Father's will.\"\n\n\"Honestly, if a theory makes the Father look less like the God Jesus revealed, I start distrusting the theory.\" *I tilt my head.* \"What part of it is catching in you most—wrath itself, or the idea of payment?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.042865000000035,"run_id":"40b75800-347a-4687-b9dd-afc3444adbbc"}
